            AppRoutes = """["/quality"]""",
            Tags = """["quality","qc","inspection","quiz"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"passingScore":80,"questionsPerQuiz":8,"shuffleOptions":true,"showExplanationsAfterSubmit":true,"questions":[{"id":"qc1","text":"You need to inspect incoming material for a specific part that has a standard checklist. What is the most efficient workflow?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Go to Quality → Inspections tab, click New Inspection, select the QC template for that part, enter the lot number, and work through the pre-populated checklist items","isCorrect":true},{"id":"b","text":"Create a new QC template from scratch each time you perform an inspection"},{"id":"c","text":"Go to the Parts module and record inspection results in the part notes field"},{"id":"d","text":"Skip the inspection and mark the lot as accepted in Inventory"}],"explanation":"QC templates define reusable checklists. When creating an inspection, selecting a template pre-populates all the checklist items. Enter the lot number for traceability, and record pass/fail results for each check."},{"id":"qc2","text":"An inspection has a results summary showing '4/6'. What does this mean?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"4 out of 6 inspectors approved the part"},{"id":"b","text":"4 out of 6 individual checklist checks passed","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The part scored 4 out of 6 on a quality rating scale"},{"id":"d","text":"4 of 6 lots in the batch were inspected"}],"explanation":"The results summary shows how many individual checklist items passed out of the total. '4/6' means 4 checks passed and 2 failed. This gives a quick at-a-glance view of inspection quality."},{"id":"qc3","text":"A customer reports a defect in parts from lot L-2024-0042. You need to find every job, PO, and bin location that used material from this lot. Where do you look?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Quality → Lots tab → search for L-2024-0042 → click the traceability button (tree icon) to see all linked jobs, production runs, POs, bin locations, and inspections","isCorrect":true},{"id":"b","text":"Run a report in the Reports module filtered by lot number"},{"id":"c","text":"Check the Inventory module for bin contents matching that lot"},{"id":"d","text":"Search for the lot number in the Kanban board search"}],"explanation":"The Lot Tracking tab has a traceability button per row (tree icon) that opens a dialog showing every linked record: jobs, production runs, purchase orders, bin locations, and QC inspections. This is the fastest way to trace a lot through your operation."},{"id":"qc4","text":"You are monitoring a critical dimension on a CNC-machined part and notice the SPC chart shows a point beyond the upper control limit (UCL). What should you expect from the system?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Nothing — the chart is informational only and does not trigger any alerts"},{"id":"b","text":"An out-of-control (OOC) event is automatically generated in the OOC Events tab, with severity based on the rule violated. If the characteristic has 'Notify on OOC' enabled, a notification is also sent.","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The system automatically stops the CNC machine via IoT integration"},{"id":"d","text":"The part status is automatically changed to Obsolete"}],"explanation":"When SPC detects an out-of-control condition (like a point beyond 3-sigma), it creates an OOC event with the appropriate severity. If the characteristic has 'Notify on OOC' enabled, relevant personnel receive a notification. The OOC event can then be acknowledged and a CAPA created if needed."},{"id":"qc5","text":"A batch of supplier-provided material fails incoming inspection. You document this as an NCR. What NCR type and detection stage should you select?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Type: Internal, Detection Stage: In Process"},{"id":"b","text":"Type: Customer, Detection Stage: Receiving"},{"id":"c","text":"Type: Supplier, Detection Stage: Receiving","isCorrect":true},{"id":"d","text":"Type: Supplier, Detection Stage: Final Inspection"}],"explanation":"Since the defect is in supplier-provided material, the NCR type is 'Supplier'. Since it was caught during incoming material inspection, the detection stage is 'Receiving'. This combination accurately categorizes the non-conformance for reporting and vendor quality tracking."},{"id":"qc6","text":"An NCR has been investigated and the quality team decides the non-conforming parts can be reworked to meet specification. What is the correct disposition code?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Use As Is"},{"id":"b","text":"Rework","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Sort & Screen"},{"id":"d","text":"Concession"}],"explanation":"'Rework' means the non-conforming material will be repaired or reworked to bring it into conformance with the specification. 'Use As Is' would accept it without changes, 'Sort & Screen' would separate good from bad, and 'Concession' would require customer approval."},{"id":"qc7","text":"A recurring quality issue has been identified through multiple NCRs. You need to perform a root cause analysis and track corrective actions to closure. Which feature should you use?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Create an ECO to document the engineering change"},{"id":"b","text":"Create a CAPA with type Corrective, link it to the NCRs, perform root cause analysis (e.g., 5 Whys or Fishbone), document corrective actions, and track through verification and effectiveness check","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Add notes to each NCR describing the corrective action taken"},{"id":"d","text":"Create a job on the Kanban board to track the fix"}],"explanation":"CAPAs are designed for systematic problem resolution. Create a Corrective CAPA from the source (here, NCR), then advance it one phase at a time with the forward-arrow action: Open → Root Cause Analysis → Action Planning → Implementation → Verification → Effectiveness Check → Closed. The root-cause method (5 Whys, Fishbone, Fault Tree, 8D, Pareto, Is/Is-Not) and write-up are phase work done after the CAPA is opened — they are not part of the create dialog, which captures type, source, title, descriptions, owner, priority, and due date."},{"id":"qc8","text":"A design change to a part requires updating the BOM, revising the drawing, and modifying the CNC program. Which Quality feature manages this controlled change?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Create an NCR to document the required changes"},{"id":"b","text":"Create an ECO with change type 'Revision', list the affected items (part, BOM, operations) with old and new values, and advance through Draft → Review → Approved → Implementation → Implemented","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Update the part record directly in the Parts module"},{"id":"d","text":"Create a CAPA to track the design change"}],"explanation":"Engineering Change Orders (ECOs) manage controlled changes to parts, processes, and documentation. Create an ECO with the appropriate change type, list all affected items with their old and new values, get approval through the review process, and track implementation status."},{"id":"qc9","text":"A digital caliper needs its annual calibration. How do you manage this in the Quality module?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Go to Quality → Gages tab, find the caliper, click it to open the detail, then click 'Record Calibration' and enter the date, result, lab name, standards used, and as-found/as-left conditions","isCorrect":true},{"id":"b","text":"Update the caliper's status to 'In Service' and change the last calibration date manually"},{"id":"c","text":"Create a maintenance work order in the Assets module"},{"id":"d","text":"Record the calibration as a time entry in Time Tracking"}],"explanation":"The Gages tab provides a complete calibration management workflow. Open the gage detail, record a new calibration with the result (Pass/Fail/Adjusted/Out of Tolerance), lab name, certificate, standards used, and as-found/as-left conditions. The system automatically updates the next calibration due date."},{"id":"qc10","text":"You scan a barcode while on the Quality page's Lots tab. What happens?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Nothing — the scanner is not active on the Quality page"},{"id":"b","text":"The scanned value fills the lot search field, letting you quickly find the scanned lot","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"A new inspection is automatically created for the scanned lot"},{"id":"d","text":"The system opens the traceability dialog for the scanned lot"}],"explanation":"The Quality page sets the scanner context to 'quality'. On the Lots tab, a barcode scan fills the lot search field with the scanned value. On the Inspections tab, it fills the inspection search field instead. This enables quick lookups on the shop floor."},{"id":"qc11","text":"What is the difference between control limits (UCL/LCL) and spec limits (USL/LSL) on an SPC chart?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"They are the same thing — just different naming conventions"},{"id":"b","text":"Control limits are calculated from actual process data and show natural variation boundaries. Spec limits are defined by engineering requirements and show the acceptable range for the product.","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Control limits are set by management, spec limits are set by customers"},{"id":"d","text":"Spec limits are always wider than control limits"}],"explanation":"Control limits (UCL/LCL) are statistically calculated from measurement data — they show the expected range of natural process variation (typically +/- 3 sigma from the mean). Spec limits (USL/LSL) are engineering requirements defined on the SPC characteristic — they define what the customer or design requires. A process can be in control (within UCL/LCL) but still out of spec, or vice versa."},{"id":"qc12","text":"A new operator opens the New Inspection dialog and asks where to build the part's checklist and tick off each check as pass or fail. What should you tell them?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The New Inspection dialog only captures Template, Job ID, Lot Number, and Notes. You pick an existing predefined template from the dropdown; the Quality page has no visual template builder and no per-check results-entry surface yet — it creates and tracks inspections rather than scoring each check.","isCorrect":true},{"id":"b","text":"Click 'Add Checklist Item' inside the dialog to build the checklist on the fly, then toggle each item pass or fail before saving"},{"id":"c","text":"Switch the dialog to Builder mode to author the template, then to Results mode to record each measurement"},{"id":"d","text":"Templates and results are both entered in the Notes field as free text"}],"explanation":"The Quality page is a create-and-track surface. QC templates are predefined for the install (seeded or admin-set-up) and are selected from a dropdown when creating an inspection — there is no in-page template builder. The dialog captures only Template, Job ID, Lot Number, and Notes, and the inspection is created In Progress. Recording pass/fail outcomes for each individual check is not yet exposed on this page."}]}"""
        });

        // ── Advanced Reference ───────────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Quality — Advanced Reference",
            Slug = "quality-reference",
            Summary = "Advanced reference for Quality: SPC control-limit recalculation, Cp/Cpk thresholds, CAPA priority scale + source taxonomy, NCR disposition codes, and gage calibration auto-scheduling.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Reference,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 90,
            AppRoutes = """["/quality"]""",
            Tags = """["quality","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## SPC Control-Limit Recalculation\n\nControl limits are not edited by hand — they are computed from recorded subgroups. Recalculation runs through `POST /api/v1/spc/characteristics/{id}/recalculate-limits` with optional `fromSubgroup` and `toSubgroup` query params to scope the baseline window. The handler:\n\n- Requires at least 2 subgroups in range (fewer throws and no limit is written).\n- Looks up the characteristic's `SampleSize` and pulls SPC constants (A2, D3, D4, d2, A3, B3, B4, c4) from a table covering sizes 2-25; sizes not in the table are linearly interpolated.\n- X-bar limits: `X̄̄ ± A2·R̄` (grand mean ± A2 times the average range). Range limits: UCL = `D4·R̄`, LCL = `D3·R̄` (LCL is 0 for sample sizes < 7 since D3 = 0).\n- Within-subgroup process sigma is estimated as `R̄ / d2`.\n- For `SampleSize >= 10`, S-chart limits are also written: center = S̄, UCL = `B4·S̄`, LCL = `B3·S̄`.\n- Recalculation deactivates every existing active `SpcControlLimit` row (`IsActive = false`) and inserts one new active row. History is preserved — old limit sets remain for audit, only one is active at a time. The active row carries `CalculatedAt`, `SampleCount`, and the `FromSubgroup`/`ToSubgroup` window it was derived from.\n\nThe chart and the OOC rule engine read the single active limit row. Gated by `CAP-QC-SPC`.\n\n## Cp / Cpk / Pp / Ppk Thresholds and Formulas\n\nCapability indices are computed during recalculation and stored on the active limit row; they are also exposed at `GET /api/v1/spc/capability/{characteristicId}`. Exact formulas:\n\n- `Cp = (USL - LSL) / (6σ)` — short-term potential, ignores centering. Uses the within-subgroup sigma (`R̄/d2`).\n- `Cpk = min[(USL - mean) / (3σ), (mean - LSL) / (3σ)]` — short-term actual, penalizes off-center processes.\n- `Pp = (USL - LSL) / (6σ_overall)` and `Ppk = min[(USL - mean) / (3σ_overall), (mean - LSL) / (3σ_overall)]` — long-term performance using the overall sigma computed from every individual reading (sample standard deviation, n-1), not the R̄/d2 estimate.\n- Guard: when sigma is 0 (no variation / single value), all four indices return 0 rather than dividing by zero.\n\nIndustry interpretation (not enforced by the app — there is no hard pass/fail gate on the index value): Cpk ≥ 1.33 is the common \"capable\" target, ≥ 1.67 for critical characteristics, and < 1.0 means the process spread exceeds the tolerance. The system never blocks data entry on a low index; it surfaces the number and relies on OOC rules for alerting. USL/LSL come from the characteristic definition and are independent of the calculated UCL/LCL.\n\n## CAPA Priority Scale and Source Taxonomy\n\n`CorrectiveAction.Priority` is a plain `int` (not an enum), defaulting to `3`. The convention is a 1-5 scale: 1 = Critical, 2 = High, 3 = Medium (default), 4 = Low, 5 = Informational. Because it is stored as an integer, values outside 1-5 are technically accepted by the model — the scale is a UI convention, not a DB constraint.\n\n`CapaSourceType` (the origin taxonomy) has seven members: `Ncr`, `CustomerComplaint`, `InternalAudit`, `ExternalAudit`, `SpcOoc`, `ManagementReview`, `Other`. `SpcOoc` is the value used when a CAPA is spawned from an out-of-control event via `POST /api/v1/spc/out-of-control/{id}/create-capa`; `Ncr` is used by `POST /api/v1/quality/ncrs/{id}/create-capa`. Both auto-stamp `SourceEntityType`/`SourceEntityId` so the CAPA links back to its origin.\n\n`CapaType` is just `Corrective` or `Preventive`. Phase fields not captured at creation — `RootCauseMethod` (`RootCauseMethod` enum: 5 Whys / Fishbone / Fault Tree / 8D / Pareto / Is-Is Not), `RootCauseAnalysis`, `EffectivenessCheckDueDate`/`EffectivenessCheckDate`, and `CapaTask` rows — are filled in as the CAPA advances through `POST /api/v1/quality/capas/{id}/advance` (Open → RootCauseAnalysis → ActionPlanning → Implementation → Verification → EffectivenessCheck → Closed).\n\n## NCR Disposition Code Reference (Reject vs Concession)\n\nThe backend enum `NcrDispositionCode` has six members: `UseAsIs`, `Rework`, `Scrap`, `ReturnToVendor`, `SortAndScreen`, `Reject`. Note the discrepancy: the canonical sixth code in the data model is `Reject`, whereas the training overview, field reference, and most quality literature use \"Concession\" as the sixth disposition. Treat them as the same slot — the persisted enum value is `Reject`; \"Concession\" is the business-facing label for the accept-with-deviation case. When reading or writing the API, use `Reject`; when reading screens or docs that say \"Concession\", map it to this code.\n\nMeaning of each: `UseAsIs` (accept as-is, no rework), `Rework` (repair to conformance), `Scrap` (discard), `ReturnToVendor` (send defective supplier material back), `SortAndScreen` (100% inspect the lot to separate good from bad), `Reject` / Concession (reject outright, or accept under documented customer concession depending on the label in use). Disposition is set as the NCR moves to the `Dispositioned` status; it does not change the affected/defective quantities.\n\n## Gage Calibration-History Auto-Scheduling\n\nRecording a calibration (`POST /api/v1/quality/gages/{id}/calibrations`) does more than append history — it reschedules and re-statuses the gage automatically:\n\n- `NextCalibrationDue = CalibratedAt + Gage.CalibrationIntervalDays` (a `DateOnly`). The same value is written onto both the new `CalibrationRecord` and the parent `Gage`, and `Gage.LastCalibratedAt` is set to the calibration timestamp.\n- Gage status auto-flips: a `Fail` result sets the gage to `OutOfService`; any other result (`Pass`, `Adjusted`, `OutOfTolerance`) sets it to `InService`. The interval clock restarts from the calibration date regardless of result.\n- `GET /api/v1/quality/gages/due?daysAhead=30` (default 30) returns every non-`Retired` gage whose `NextCalibrationDue` falls on or before the cutoff, ordered by soonest-due. This is the surface a calibration coordinator polls; the `DueForCalibration` status itself is a manual/derived state, not auto-set by the passage of time — \"due\" is computed from the date, while the stored `Status` only flips on a recorded calibration or explicit edit.\n- `CalibratedById` is stamped from the auth context, not the request body. Validation requires `CalibratedAt` and a valid `Result` enum value.\n\nGage and calibration endpoints are gated by `CAP-QC-GAGE`.\n\n## Capability and Role Gating Map (Quality)\n\nQuality spans several controllers, each with its own capability — disabling one capability hides only that slice:\n\n- `CAP-QC-INSPECTION` — QC inspections and templates (`QualityController`, base gate).\n- `CAP-INV-LOTS` — lot records and traceability (`LotsController`; roles Admin/Manager/Engineer/ProductionWorker).\n- `CAP-QC-SPC` — all SPC characteristics, measurements, charts, OOC events, and limit recalculation (`SpcController`).\n- `CAP-QC-NCR` — both NCRs and CAPAs. The CAPA endpoints live on the NCR controller and inherit its `CAP-QC-NCR` gate, so a standalone `CAP-QC-CAPA` capability exists in the catalog but is not what actually gates CAPA writes today. NCR/CAPA writes require role Admin or Manager.\n- `CAP-QC-GAGE` — gages and calibration records.\n- `CAP-MD-ECO` — engineering change orders (the ECO endpoints sit on `QualityController` but carry their own `CAP-MD-ECO` gate; roles Admin/Manager/Engineer).\n\nOther QC capabilities exist in the catalog for features not yet surfaced on the Quality page: `CAP-QC-COA`, `CAP-QC-COMPLIANCE-FORMS`, `CAP-QC-FMEA`, `CAP-QC-PPAP`, `CAP-QC-RECALL`.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        Log.Information("Seeded Quality training modules");
    }
